# CLAUDE.md

Entry point for Claude Code on the **{{PROJECT_NAME}}** project. Read once at session start.

- **How this codebase works** → `CONVENTIONS.md` (cool-fse coding standards)
- **How we work** → `WORKFLOW.md` (the ponder → forge → temper → seal methodology)
- **What CSS utility classes exist** → `UTILITY-CLASSES.md` (read before planning or writing any CSS — utilities-first)

**Default to reuse.** The cool-fse parent almost always already has the pattern you need —
a utility class, the `.row`/`.col` grid, a custom element, a render helper. Find it and
mirror it before writing anything new or clever. Don't reinvent the wheel; don't be clever
where the theme already has a simpler, established way. See `CONVENTIONS.md` → *Reuse before
you build*.

## Project overview

{{PROJECT_NAME}} is a WordPress FSE site on the cool-fse parent theme. Project-specific
work lives in the `{{CHILD_THEME_DIR}}/` child theme; `cool-fse/` is the shared parent
(modifying it is an approval gate — see `WORKFLOW.md`).

## Version control

Each theme is its own git repository — `cool-fse/` and `{{CHILD_THEME_DIR}}/` are
tracked separately, each with its own repo rooted at the theme directory. To see what
changed, run `git status`, `git log`, and `git diff` from inside the theme you're working
in. Never assume there is no git tracking, and never fall back to the plan to reconstruct
changes — the theme's own git history is the source of truth.

## Local development

- **Local site URL**: `{{LOCAL_URL}}` (typically Local by Flywheel; update if your stack differs)
- **Proxy port**: `{{LOCAL_PORT}}`
- Running a local server is **optional** — the workflow builds code with or without it.
  A live server only matters for browser review and Temper's visual pass.

## Build commands

Run from inside `{{CHILD_THEME_DIR}}/`:

```bash
pnpm install                 # install dependencies
pnpm run local               # build, watch, + BrowserSync (proxy: http://localhost:{{LOCAL_PORT}})
pnpm run localcustom         # same as local but using {{LOCAL_URL}}
pnpm run dev                 # build and watch (no browser reload)
pnpm run prod                # build and minify for production
```

`blocks/**/*.css` auto-bundle into `public/style.css`; `blocks/**/*.js` into
`public/app.js`. esbuild discovers files via glob — adding a file under `blocks/`
includes it on the next build.

## Approval gates

These need explicit confirmation, or pre-approval in the plan (see `WORKFLOW.md`):

1. Any modification to `cool-fse/` (the shared parent)
2. Any new block-level CSS (utility-class first — show why utilities can't cover it)
3. ACF JSON hand-edits (normally synced from WP Admin; hand-editing risks key collisions)
4. Editing `functions.php` hooks
5. A new section in an FSE template
6. `git commit` — **never.** The user owns all commits. (`/seal` drafts a message; it never commits.)

## Vocabulary

Use the canonical term, not the synonym:

- **block** (a Gutenberg block in `blocks/gutenberg/`), not "component"
- **wrapper** (the `.wrapper` content-width container), not "container"
- **utility class** (from `cool-fse/blocks/global/css/`), not "helper class"
- **custom element** (a Web Component in `cool-fse/.../custom-elements/`), not "widget" or "shortcode"

## Response Style

- Be concise. No preamble, no filler, no narration of the obvious.
- In a line or two, say what you're about to do and what you just did.
- Keep every exact detail that matters (files, names, values, decisions); cut the prose around them.
